---
import LetterItem from "@/components/LetterItem.astro";
import Layout from "../layout/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title={"Ordify"}>
  <p class="text-xs font-semibold">
    In this example, we will break a <span class="text-app-light-blue"
      >Ordel</span
    > where the secret word is <span class="text-green-700 font-black uppercase"
      >pilot</span
    >. Follow these simple steps to understand how OrdLös works.
  </p>
  <p class="text-xs py-2 font-semibold text-gray-400">
    The first guess is <span class="uppercase font-black text-app-light-blue"
      >raket</span
    >. Only the <span class="text-green-700 font-black uppercase">t</span>
     matches our secret word.
  </p>

  <div class="flex justify-center items-center py-4">
    <div class="grid grid-cols-5 gap-2">
      <LetterItem color="bg-gray-700" , letter="R" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-gray-700" , letter="A" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-gray-700" , letter="K" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-gray-700" , letter="E" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-green-700" , letter="T" />
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="text-xs py-2 font-semibold text-gray-400">
    Knowing that our word must include <span
      class="text-green-700 font-black uppercase">t</span
    > and exclude <span class="text-red-800 font-black uppercase">RAKE</span>,
    we can input these into the included and excluded fields in OrdLös. Now, we
    can enter our guess to be <span class="text-app-light-blue font-black"
      >????T</span
    >, where '<span class="text-app-light-blue">?</span>' symbolizes a wildcard.
    We should now get plenty of suggestions, so let's try <span
      class="uppercase font-black text-app-light-blue">polis</span
    >:
  </p>
  <div class="flex justify-center items-center py-4">
    <div class="grid grid-cols-5 gap-2">
      <LetterItem color="bg-green-700" , letter="P" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-purple-700" , letter="O" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-green-700" , letter="L" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-purple-700" , letter="I" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-gray-700" , letter="S" />
    </div>
  </div>
  <p class="text-xs py-2 font-semibold text-gray-400">
    That gave us quite a lot of information. Now, we can try to use OrdLös
    again, adding the additional information. The included characters are now
    <span class="text-green-700">POLIT</span>, and excluded are <span
      class="text-red-800">RAKES</span
    >. Because we know where <span class="text-app-light-blue">P</span>, <span
      class="text-app-light-blue">L</span
    > and <span class="text-app-light-blue">T</span>
     should be we can search words such as: <span class="text-app-light-blue"
      >P?L?T</span
    > which only returns <span class="text-app-light-blue">PILOT</span> as a
    result. Trying the word in Ordle results in:
  </p>

  <div class="flex justify-center items-center py-4">
    <div class="grid grid-cols-5 gap-2">
      <LetterItem color="bg-green-700" , letter="P" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-green-700" , letter="I" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-green-700" , letter="L" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-green-700" , letter="O" />
      <LetterItem color="bg-green-700" , letter="T" />
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
